      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the yellowing of your tomato plants' lower leaves is a common sign of a nutrient deficiency, often due to poor soil drainage or compacted soil. You might want to consider adding some organic matter, like compost, to improve the soil structure. Also, ensure your plants are getting enough water, but not too much, as overwatering can lead to root rot and further nutrient issues. If the problem persists, you might want to test your soil's pH level to see if it's too acidic or alkaline, as this can also affect nutrient uptake. Remember, a well-balanced soil is key to healthy plants, and sometimes a little extra care is all it takes to keep those pesky tomato plants happy. Happy gardening!",
