    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think it might be a nutrient thing though since the yellowing is pretty specific. could it be a nitrogen deficiency? how do i check if the nitrogen levels are low enough to cause this and what should i add to the soil to fix it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the yellowing of your tomato plants' lower leaves could indeed be a sign of nitrogen deficiency. Nitrogen is a crucial nutrient for plant growth, and a lack of it can lead to yellowing leaves, especially at the bottom of the plant where the roots are less efficient at absorbing nutrients.\n\nTo check if your soil has low nitrogen levels, you can perform a simple soil test. You can purchase a soil test kit from your local garden center or nursery, or you can send a sample to a professional soil testing service. These tests will provide you with a detailed analysis of your soil's nutrient levels, including nitrogen.\n\nIf your soil test confirms a nitrogen deficiency, there are several ways to add nitrogen to your soil:\n\n1. Organic matter: Adding compost, manure, or other organic matter can help increase the nitrogen content in your soil. These materials break down over time, releasing nitrogen and other nutrients into the soil.\n\n2. Fertilizers: You can also use a nitrogen-rich fertilizer to quickly boost the nitrogen levels in your soil. Look for fertilizers labeled as \"high in nitrogen\" or \"complete fertilizer,\" which contain a balanced mix of nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium. Be sure to follow the manufacturer's instructions for application rates and timing.",
